What is a Link in Linux?

A link is a reference (shortcut) to a file.

There are two types:

Hard link

Soft link (Symbolic link)

ğŸ”¹ Hard Link
Definition:

ğŸ‘‰ A hard link is another name for the same file (same inode).

Explanation:

Points directly to the inode

Original file and hard link are equal

Deleting one does not delete data

Example:
ln file1 file1_hard

Key Points:

Shares same inode number

Data remains until all hard links are deleted

Cannot link directories

Cannot cross file systems

ğŸ”¹ Soft Link (Symbolic Link)
Definition:

ğŸ‘‰ A soft link is a shortcut that points to the file name/path.

Explanation:

Has a different inode

Points to the original file path

If original file is deleted â†’ link breaks

Example:
ln -s file1 file1_soft

Key Points:

Different inode number

Can link directories

Can cross file systems

Breaks if original file is removed

ğŸ”¥ Hard Link vs Soft Link (Interview Table)
Feature	Hard Link	Soft Link
Inode	Same	Different
File type	Regular file	Shortcut
If original deleted	Works	Broken
Cross filesystem	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Link directories	âŒ No	âœ… Yes
Size	Same as file	Very small
ğŸ”¹ Real-World Example
Hard Link:

Think of two names for the same person ğŸ‘¤
Deleting one name doesnâ€™t remove the person.

Soft Link:

Think of a Google Maps shortcut ğŸ“
If the address changes, shortcut fails.

ğŸ”¹ Commands to Check
ls -li


ğŸ‘‰ Shows inode numbers (same inode = hard link)

ls -l


ğŸ‘‰ Shows soft link (l) and arrow (->)

â­ One-Line Interview Answer

A hard link points directly to the inode and remains valid even if the original file is deleted, while a soft link points to the file path and breaks if the original file is removed.


Definition (Interview Answer):
ğŸ‘‰ umask (User Mask) defines the default permission that is REMOVED when a new file or directory is created.

Simple Explanation

Linux has default maximum permissions

Files â†’ 666 (rw-rw-rw-)

Directories â†’ 777 (rwxrwxrwx)

umask subtracts permissions from these defaults

Formula (VERY IMPORTANT)
Final Permission = Default Permission â€“ umask

Default umask Values
User Type	umask
Normal user	002
Root	022
Example 1ï¸âƒ£ (Most Common Interview One)
umask = 022
File:
666 - 022 = 644 â†’ rw-r--r--

Directory:
777 - 022 = 755 â†’ rwxr-xr-x

Do files and directories use umask by default?

ğŸ‘‰ YES.
Whenever you create a new file or directory, Linux automatically applies the umask to decide its default permissions.

Think of umask like a safety filter ğŸ›¡ï¸
Even if full access is possible, umask removes dangerous permissions by default.
